  "summaries": [
    {"book":"2 Kings","chapter":1,"summary":"After Ahaziah falls through a lattice, Elijah intercepts his messengers to Baal-zebub, pronounces the king's death, and calls down fire on two companies of fifty."},
    {"book":"2 Kings","chapter":2,"summary":"Elijah ascends to heaven in a chariot of fire; Elisha receives his mantle and double portion, heals the waters of Jericho, and curses mocking youths."},
    {"book":"2 Kings","chapter":3,"summary":"The kings of Israel, Judah, and Edom ally against Moab; Elisha provides water and victory, but the Moabite king's sacrifice halts the campaign."},
    {"book":"2 Kings","chapter":4,"summary":"Elisha multiplies a widow's oil, promises a son to the Shunammite woman and raises him from death, purifies poisoned pottage, and feeds a hundred men."},
    {"book":"2 Kings","chapter":5,"summary":"Naaman the Syrian commander is healed of leprosy by washing in the Jordan at Elisha's command; Gehazi is struck with Naaman's leprosy for taking gifts deceitfully."},
    {"book":"2 Kings","chapter":6,"summary":"Elisha causes an axe head to float, reveals heavenly hosts to his servant, blinds the Syrian army, and Samaria endures a devastating siege and famine."},
    {"book":"2 Kings","chapter":7,"summary":"Elisha prophesies the end of the famine; four lepers discover the Syrians have fled, and the doubting officer is trampled in the rush for food."},
    {"book":"2 Kings","chapter":8,"summary":"The Shunammite's land is restored; Elisha foretells Hazael's rise to Syria's throne, and the wicked reigns of Jehoram and Ahaziah in Judah are recorded."},
    {"book":"2 Kings","chapter":9,"summary":"Elisha sends a prophet to anoint Jehu king over Israel; Jehu kills Joram and Ahaziah, and Jezebel is thrown from a window and eaten by dogs."},
    {"book":"2 Kings","chapter":10,"summary":"Jehu slaughters the seventy sons of Ahab, the brethren of Ahaziah, and all the prophets and worshippers of Baal, purging his cult from Israel."},
    {"book":"2 Kings","chapter":11,"summary":"Athaliah usurps the throne of Judah, but Jehoiada the priest hides Joash and after six years crowns him king, executing Athaliah and renewing the covenant."},
    {"book":"2 Kings","chapter":12,"summary":"Joash repairs the temple under Jehoiada's direction, but later sends the temple treasures to Hazael to buy off a Syrian invasion and is assassinated by his servants."},
    {"book":"2 Kings","chapter":13,"summary":"Jehoahaz and Jehoash reign in Israel under Aramean oppression; Elisha's deathbed prophecy limits Israel's victories, and a corpse revives upon touching Elisha's bones."},
    {"book":"2 Kings","chapter":14,"summary":"Amaziah of Judah defeats Edom but is humbled by Jehoash of Israel; Jeroboam II restores Israel's borders, and Amaziah is assassinated in Lachish."},
    {"book":"2 Kings","chapter":15,"summary":"A series of short reigns in Israel marked by assassinations (Zechariah, Shallum, Pekahiah, Pekah), while Azariah and Jotham reign in Judah and Assyria begins deportations."},
    {"book":"2 Kings","chapter":16,"summary":"Ahaz of Judah practices abominations, appeals to Assyria against Syria and Israel, and remodels the temple altar after a pagan design seen in Damascus."},
    {"book":"2 Kings","chapter":17,"summary":"Samaria falls to Assyria and Israel is carried into exile; the chapter gives a theological explanation of the catastrophe and describes the foreign colonists settled in the land."},
    {"book":"2 Kings","chapter":18,"summary":"Hezekiah removes the high places and breaks Nehushtan; he rebels against Assyria, and Sennacherib's field commander Rabshakeh taunts Jerusalem with blasphemous speeches."},
    {"book":"2 Kings","chapter":19,"summary":"Hezekiah spreads Sennacherib's letter before the Lord; Isaiah delivers a prophecy of deliverance, and the angel of the Lord destroys 185,000 Assyrians overnight."},
    {"book":"2 Kings","chapter":20,"summary":"Hezekiah is healed of his illness and receives a fifteen-year extension of life with the sign of the retreating shadow; he unwisely shows his treasures to Babylonian envoys."},
    {"book":"2 Kings","chapter":21,"summary":"Manasseh's reign reverses Hezekiah's reforms with unprecedented idolatry and violence; Amon succeeds him briefly and is assassinated by his own servants."},
    {"book":"2 Kings","chapter":22,"summary":"Josiah commissions temple repairs; Hilkiah discovers the Book of the Law, and the prophetess Huldah confirms coming judgment but promises Josiah will be spared from seeing it."},
    {"book":"2 Kings","chapter":23,"summary":"Josiah leads the most thorough religious reform in Judah's history, purging all idolatry and renewing the Passover, but is killed at Megiddo by Pharaoh Neco."},
    {"book":"2 Kings","chapter":24,"summary":"Jehoiakim rebels against Babylon and dies; Jehoiachin surrenders Jerusalem and is deported to Babylon along with the temple treasures and leading citizens."},
    {"book":"2 Kings","chapter":25,"summary":"Nebuchadnezzar destroys Jerusalem and the temple, exiles the remaining population, appoints Gedaliah as governor who is assassinated, and later releases Jehoiachin from prison in Babylon."}
  ],
